T1  - On syndicate sharing rules for unanimous project rankings
AU  - Gandhi, Devinder K.
AU  - Hausmann, Robert
AU  - Saunders, Anthony
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 9
IS  - 4
SP  - 517
EP  - 534
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/12/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0378-4266(85)90004-4
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0378426685900044
AB  - This paper extends the notion of individual certainty equivalent to group certainty equivalent, in order to derive sharing rules that ensure unanimity on project rankings within a syndicate. A constrained maximization problem is set up with optimal project-specific sharing rules as the solution. It is shown that the group certainty equivalent construct allows for experimental derivation of a syndicate's preference function from a procedure parallel to that presently employed for deriving preference functions of individuals. The analysis potentially has a role in examining the nature of optimal compensation systems (sharing rules) for closely held (non-traded) corporations and partnerships.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Commercial bank refinancing and economic stability: An analysis of european features
AU  - Langohr, Herwig
AU  - Santomero, Anthony M.
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 9
IS  - 4
SP  - 535
EP  - 552
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/12/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0378-4266(85)90005-6
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0378426685900056
AB  - This paper investigates the effect of two types of central bank advances, viz, Lombarding and Rediscounting, on the economy. We conclude that the root of the distinction is the differential collateralization of these two forms of advances. The results suggest that while both methods of refinancing reduce interest-rate movement, Rediscounting dampens the impact of base money and real-sector disturbances. Debt-equity shifts have greater price effects with Rediscounting than with Lombarding. The paper also investigates the effects of a pegged-rate pricing policy. It is shown that a pegged-rate policy is an intermediary between fixed and market rate regimes.
ER  - 

